hands_on_practices.problem:
A non-contextual hidden variable (NCHV) theory posits that the result of any quantum measurement is predetermined by a set of hidden variables. Specifically, for any observable $O$, there exists a pre-assigned value (or outcome) $v(O)$, which is one of the eigenvalues of $O$. A key assumption is non-contextuality: the value $v(O)$ is independent of which other compatible (i.e., commuting) observables are measured alongside $O$. Furthermore, if a set of mutually commuting observables $\{O_1, O_2, \dots, O_n\}$ satisfies an algebraic identity $\prod_{k=1}^n O_k = c I$, where $I$ is the identity operator and $c$ is a scalar, then their pre-assigned values must satisfy the same numerical relation: $\prod_{k=1}^n v(O_k) = c$.

Consider a system of two spin-1/2 particles. The observables are constructed from the Pauli operators $\sigma_{a,k}$, where $a \in \{x,y,z\}$ denotes the Pauli matrix and $k \in \{1,2\}$ indicates the particle. These operators obey $\sigma_a^2=I$ and $\sigma_a \sigma_b = i \epsilon_{abc} \sigma_c$ for $a \neq b$. Operators acting on different particles commute, e.g., $[\sigma_{a,1}, \sigma_{b,2}] = 0$.

The nine observables of the Peres-Mermin square are arranged in a $3 \times 3$ matrix $A$, where $A_{ij}$ is the observable in row $i$ and column $j$:
$$
A = \begin{pmatrix}
A_{11} & A_{12} & A_{13} \\
A_{21} & A_{22} & A_{23} \\
A_{31} & A_{32} & A_{33}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_{x,1} & \sigma_{x,2} & \sigma_{x,1}\sigma_{x,2} \\
\sigma_{y,2} & \sigma_{y,1} & \sigma_{y,1}\sigma_{y,2} \\
\sigma_{x,1}\sigma_{y,2} & \sigma_{y,1}\sigma_{x,2} & \sigma_{z,1}\sigma_{z,2}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Each operator $A_{ij}$ has eigenvalues $\pm 1$, so the corresponding NCHV-assigned value $v_{ij} \equiv v(A_{ij})$ must be either $+1$ or $-1$. The observables in any given row or any given column are mutually commuting.

The NCHV framework leads to a logical contradiction. Your task is to quantify this contradiction. Let $P_R = \prod_{i=1}^3 \left( \prod_{j=1}^3 v_{ij} \right)$ be the product of all nine assigned values, grouped by rows. Let $P_C = \prod_{j=1}^3 \left( \prod_{i=1}^3 v_{ij} \right)$ be the same product, but grouped by columns. From the commutativity of scalar multiplication, it is clear that $P_R$ and $P_C$ must be equal. However, applying the NCHV rules based on the operator algebra yields a paradoxical result.

Derive the value of the ratio $\frac{P_R}{P_C}$ that is predicted by applying the NCHV rules to the quantum mechanical operator algebra of the Peres-Mermin square.
